1
00:00:06,320 --> 00:00:09,322
I'm Ilian Mellon, or Natsali Lahet outside of the internet.

2
00:00:09,582 --> 00:00:11,123
I make art that people call games.

3
00:00:12,023 --> 00:00:14,465
I started doing this in the late 90s, early 2000s.

4
00:00:14,805 --> 00:00:17,367
And at that time, it was considered net art.

5
00:00:17,407 --> 00:00:19,048
But my interest in art on computers

6
00:00:19,088 --> 00:00:20,689
has always been more complex than that.

7
00:00:21,610 --> 00:00:24,031
My most recent project is Everything is Going to be OK.

8
00:00:29,640 --> 00:00:33,661
As you can imagine, this sort of work isn't exactly financially sustainable.

9
00:00:33,861 --> 00:00:35,121
It doesn't pay for itself.

10
00:00:35,241 --> 00:00:39,082
People do support it and sometimes pay with a pay-what-you-want option, but I largely

11
00:00:39,122 --> 00:00:40,762
pay for making this out of my own pocket.

12
00:00:41,502 --> 00:00:46,323
The pattern my career has taken over the years is to do contracting work, mostly web development,

13
00:00:46,363 --> 00:00:47,363
to pay for making this.

14
00:00:48,223 --> 00:00:51,704
I live as meagerly as possible so that all my resources can go into this.

15
00:00:52,144 --> 00:00:53,104
This is my passion.

16
00:00:53,184 --> 00:00:54,325
It's something that I have to do.

17
00:00:54,525 --> 00:00:56,965
I view myself as an artist, and making this is my drive.

18
00:00:57,965 --> 00:01:04,747
The conversations of business and financial success surrounding my art have been a strong point of contention throughout the time that I have been doing this.

19
00:01:05,467 --> 00:01:10,629
To me it's not about the money, to everyone else it should be, otherwise I am a failure as a functional member of society.

20
00:01:11,549 --> 00:01:15,530
Good work is often measured against how much money it has made in order to be considered good.

21
00:01:22,735 --> 00:01:24,696
That being said, I'm not a business success,

22
00:01:24,936 --> 00:01:27,698
but I am going to discuss my own personal measurement

23
00:01:27,738 --> 00:01:29,579
for success and the success of my art.

24
00:01:30,399 --> 00:01:33,041
I very much believe that some of the important things in life

25
00:01:33,101 --> 00:01:35,482
can't be quantified by monetary value,

26
00:01:35,522 --> 00:01:36,543
and art is one of those.

27
00:01:37,343 --> 00:01:40,005
To me, art is about dissent, raising questions,

28
00:01:40,205 --> 00:01:42,126
pointing at the beauty of life, or making

29
00:01:42,166 --> 00:01:43,607
the darkness in life tolerable.

30
00:01:44,327 --> 00:01:47,169
It's uniquely expressing views and giving a voice to topics

31
00:01:47,209 --> 00:01:48,329
that need to be expressed.

32
00:01:49,410 --> 00:01:51,211
Sometimes these topics aren't popular.

33
00:01:51,612 --> 00:01:55,795
There's a comfort zone of acceptable or successful content that people are willing to consume,

34
00:01:55,875 --> 00:01:59,377
and I feel like art is about challenging that comfort zone and pushing for more.

35
00:02:00,218 --> 00:02:02,380
Art like this doesn't sell like entertainment does.

36
00:02:02,600 --> 00:02:05,562
Most art relies on grants or external support to exist.

37
00:02:08,124 --> 00:02:11,146
For example, my grandfather was a popular sculptor in Slovenia.

38
00:02:12,617 --> 00:02:15,238
His work was strongly anti-capitalist.

39
00:02:15,499 --> 00:02:17,940
Most of his best was socialist-inspired commentary

40
00:02:17,980 --> 00:02:20,461
about, for example, rich people putting poor people

41
00:02:20,501 --> 00:02:22,222
into meat grinders in order to make meals

42
00:02:22,262 --> 00:02:23,242
for the rich upper class,

43
00:02:23,782 --> 00:02:25,463
poor people carrying crosses up a hill

44
00:02:25,503 --> 00:02:27,784
with rich people depicted as devils in top hats

45
00:02:27,864 --> 00:02:28,825
mocking them, and so on.

46
00:02:29,585 --> 00:02:31,246
As you can imagine, his work would sometimes

47
00:02:31,286 --> 00:02:32,006
get him in trouble.

48
00:02:32,686 --> 00:02:35,208
This was true for many artists coming from his background.

49
00:02:35,548 --> 00:02:36,468
Art raised dissent.

50
00:02:36,748 --> 00:02:38,549
On the other hand, this dissent wasn't

51
00:02:38,589 --> 00:02:40,230
a sustainable financial model.

52
00:02:41,470 --> 00:02:43,593
But this is why our society needs art.

53
00:02:43,994 --> 00:02:45,816
Art is a conduit for social change.

54
00:02:51,890 --> 00:02:54,372
Despite the obvious financial or social setbacks,

55
00:02:54,532 --> 00:02:55,853
artists will make art anyway.

56
00:02:56,033 --> 00:02:58,896
This is not sustainable for me, but making art matters to me

57
00:02:58,936 --> 00:03:01,878
because art is vital for the health of a society.

58
00:03:02,659 --> 00:03:04,881
So here's an interesting challenge worth considering.

59
00:03:05,141 --> 00:03:07,203
Art like this will often not be recognized

60
00:03:07,263 --> 00:03:09,825
in the historic time frame that it is made in and for.

61
00:03:10,526 --> 00:03:12,407
It will often be laughed at, but these struggles

62
00:03:12,447 --> 00:03:14,449
can lead to social change and inspire others

63
00:03:14,489 --> 00:03:16,551
to work outside of established comfort zones.

64
00:03:18,430 --> 00:03:22,834
Some messages are too political, too edgy, too controversial, but need to be said anyway.

65
00:03:23,395 --> 00:03:26,838
It's difficult to weigh money as a metric for success against art like this.

66
00:03:27,599 --> 00:03:30,702
The going stereotype is that many artists die in poverty.

67
00:03:31,123 --> 00:03:34,366
What we laugh at today ends up being the misunderstood genius of tomorrow

68
00:03:34,406 --> 00:03:36,008
whose work, after death, makes money.

69
00:03:37,121 --> 00:03:38,803
Were they a failure while alive?

70
00:03:39,143 --> 00:03:41,826
Can we recognize this work while it's socially relevant?

71
00:03:42,066 --> 00:03:43,788
Did sales define their art's value?

72
00:03:44,549 --> 00:03:46,711
You cannot place a price on things like dissent,

73
00:03:46,751 --> 00:03:48,813
yet artistic dissent is a critical component

74
00:03:48,833 --> 00:03:50,095
to the health of a society,

75
00:03:50,155 --> 00:03:51,556
and things like this improve life.

76
00:03:52,577 --> 00:03:54,598
Here, I don't think money can define value.

77
00:03:54,738 --> 00:03:57,719
For example, you cannot financially measure sentimental value.

78
00:03:58,280 --> 00:04:02,922
One item might be priceless to one individual, and to everyone else it is trash.

79
00:04:03,542 --> 00:04:07,744
Applying a price on some things may even diminish their value because it does not take into

80
00:04:07,784 --> 00:04:11,565
account things like human impact, social impact, sentimental value, or personal worth.

81
00:04:13,912 --> 00:04:16,313
My first project was released in 1999.

82
00:04:16,433 --> 00:04:18,894
It was political commentary about poverty, war,

83
00:04:18,974 --> 00:04:20,215
homelessness, and refugees.

84
00:04:20,915 --> 00:04:22,376
And yeah, that's the name, Blue Suburbia.

85
00:04:23,236 --> 00:04:25,937
Most of it was presented as interactive literature,

86
00:04:25,957 --> 00:04:28,058
a combination of an animated feature

87
00:04:28,078 --> 00:04:30,599
that you interact with and experience the writing in.

88
00:04:31,120 --> 00:04:32,960
You unravel messages as you interact.

89
00:04:33,301 --> 00:04:34,961
Over the years, I have received what feels like

90
00:04:34,981 --> 00:04:36,782
thousands of messages from people saying

91
00:04:36,802 --> 00:04:38,983
that it has helped them, touched them,

92
00:04:39,123 --> 00:04:40,604
changed their life, made them want

93
00:04:40,624 --> 00:04:41,785
to pursue a creative career.

94
00:04:42,345 --> 00:04:44,567
and often help them through some serious dark times.

95
00:04:45,288 --> 00:04:46,849
I used to get about a message every day

96
00:04:46,909 --> 00:04:49,171
because the project had a stylist email form

97
00:04:49,231 --> 00:04:50,512
that fit one of the environments.

98
00:04:51,333 --> 00:04:53,095
I've also received a handful of messages

99
00:04:53,135 --> 00:04:54,876
from people that said that it saved their life.

100
00:04:57,479 --> 00:05:00,201
If you make work that speaks to a deeper human condition

101
00:05:00,561 --> 00:05:02,964
and admits a type of brokenness in our society,

102
00:05:03,044 --> 00:05:05,106
I feel like it's a message of solidarity

103
00:05:05,166 --> 00:05:07,047
for others that are undergoing the same.

104
00:05:08,165 --> 00:05:12,128
Many of these emails were very personal, but there is something about art that gets people

105
00:05:12,188 --> 00:05:13,770
to open up and examine their lives.

106
00:05:14,391 --> 00:05:16,432
Art like this makes people feel less alone.

107
00:05:16,633 --> 00:05:20,696
The topic might be dark, but the fact that it admits this darkness speaks to a type of

108
00:05:20,756 --> 00:05:20,957
hope.

109
00:05:21,697 --> 00:05:24,600
Even when admitting hopelessness, that admission gives people hope.

110
00:05:25,080 --> 00:05:27,563
Like I said, it speaks tremendously to solidarity.

111
00:05:28,544 --> 00:05:33,068
It was a lot to take in at the time, but at the same time, it showed me how important

112
00:05:33,088 --> 00:05:34,349
it is to make stuff like this.

113
00:05:36,822 --> 00:05:42,623
One conversation that I think about sometimes was a kid in Japan that emailed me thanking me for this project.

114
00:05:42,683 --> 00:05:47,164
They said that they were inspired to make a virtual simulation to help their friend stop self-harming.

115
00:05:47,784 --> 00:05:51,685
Their idea was if they could do it in a virtual environment, they wouldn't do it in real life.

116
00:05:52,505 --> 00:05:56,766
On the surface, this is very grim, but this was a real problem that they wanted to fix.

117
00:05:57,307 --> 00:06:02,788
This is exactly what art is suited for, addressing issues that you won't be able to address in any other capacity,

118
00:06:02,848 --> 00:06:04,408
especially in a consumer entertainment.

119
00:06:05,189 --> 00:06:09,398
It's about challenging social stigma and talking about things we don't talk about.

120
00:06:10,260 --> 00:06:15,091
It was a very personal conversation, but this is exactly the value measurement that I quantify art against.

121
00:06:16,435 --> 00:06:18,336
The human value is the true value here.

122
00:06:19,057 --> 00:06:21,599
My peers would criticize me for throwing my talents away

123
00:06:21,639 --> 00:06:23,220
on social criticism in my art.

124
00:06:23,260 --> 00:06:25,362
For example, why does something this beautiful

125
00:06:25,402 --> 00:06:28,345
have to be so depressing, anti-capitalist, heavy-handed,

126
00:06:28,745 --> 00:06:29,766
have this kind of message?

127
00:06:30,386 --> 00:06:32,348
At the time in these commercial circles,

128
00:06:32,488 --> 00:06:34,950
it was very uncool to talk about social injustice,

129
00:06:35,010 --> 00:06:36,171
poverty, war, and so on.

130
00:06:37,012 --> 00:06:38,432
This was a very commercial crowd.

131
00:06:38,472 --> 00:06:40,093
They were, by popular standards,

132
00:06:40,133 --> 00:06:41,513
very successful in their business.

133
00:06:41,993 --> 00:06:45,174
Why risk appearing opinionated and controversially so

134
00:06:45,234 --> 00:06:46,075
if you can make money?

135
00:06:46,755 --> 00:06:48,115
Challenging things is risky,

136
00:06:48,195 --> 00:06:51,136
but it is exactly this risk that makes art so valuable.

137
00:06:53,130 --> 00:06:55,071
So it was an interesting contrast.

138
00:06:55,272 --> 00:06:57,793
To my peers, I was a failure and wasted talent.

139
00:06:57,913 --> 00:06:59,974
To people that played this, I changed their lives.

140
00:07:00,554 --> 00:07:02,015
So how do you place value on this?

141
00:07:02,695 --> 00:07:04,416
If I quit pursuing this art, I would

142
00:07:04,436 --> 00:07:07,158
be a successful creative professional.

143
00:07:07,738 --> 00:07:10,059
If I pursued this art, then I am socially

144
00:07:10,099 --> 00:07:12,381
viewed as lacking ambition or wasting my talent.

145
00:07:13,181 --> 00:07:15,902
How our culture dictates value has always fascinated me.

146
00:07:16,482 --> 00:07:20,024
If we didn't measure value by money, then I feel like art would matter more.

147
00:07:20,464 --> 00:07:24,666
Money serves a purpose, but it isn't the end-all defining factor of success.

148
00:07:25,426 --> 00:07:29,368
To me, lives touched, people influenced, making the world better is what matters.

149
00:07:29,989 --> 00:07:32,510
As artists, we have a social responsibility to do that.

150
00:07:34,673 --> 00:07:37,254
I realize how cheesy that sounds, but this is why I do it.

151
00:07:37,414 --> 00:07:41,116
I believe artists should exercise their talents in a way that will make the world better,

152
00:07:41,576 --> 00:07:43,917
bring social change, or challenge people to be better.

153
00:07:44,677 --> 00:07:46,418
We assert humanity through our work.

154
00:07:47,018 --> 00:07:51,820
There's something valuable to be learned from art and artistic descent in regards to how

155
00:07:51,840 --> 00:07:55,581
we measure business success, financial success, or even entertainment success.

156
00:07:56,341 --> 00:08:00,843
The bigger picture here being how we can help society and benefit those around us through

157
00:08:00,883 --> 00:08:01,203
our work.

